The goal at this point is to show that for any `r : ↥(valuation K).integer`, the element `algebraMap K L r.1` is in `↑(valuation L).integer`.
This means we need to prove `valuation L (algebraMap K L r.1) ≤ 0`.
Given that `r` is in `↑(valuation K).integer`, we have `valuation K r.1 ≤ 0`.
Since `L` is a `ValuativeExtension` of `K`, we have `map_val : valuation K → valuation L` such that for any `k : K`, `valuation L (algebraMap K L k) = map_val (valuation K k)`.
Applying this to `r.1`, we get `valuation L (algebraMap K L r.1) = map_val (valuation K r.1)`.
Since `valuation K r.1 ≤ 0`, and `map_val` preserves order (as per `ValuativeExtension.map_val`), we get `map_val (valuation K r.1) ≤ map_val 0`.
Since `map_val 0 = 0` (as `0` in the image of `valuation K` maps to `0` in `valuation L`), we have `valuation L (algebraMap K L r.1) ≤ 0`.
This proves that `algebraMap K L r.1` is in `↑(valuation L).integer`.

